  "market_context": "ES daily chart shows a bullish fair value gap below current price with an old swing low resting just above it, serving as draw on liquidity. Higher time frame bias points lower into the daily FVG and old low.",
  "key_observation": "External-to-internal liquidity setup: an old daily low sits above an unfilled daily fair value gap, and on the hourly an old high is swept with NQ showing SMT divergence, providing confluence for a 5-minute short entry above midnight open.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the daily ES chart, identify a fair value gap below price with an old low resting directly above it as the draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the hourly chart, mark out the midnight open, and look for an hourly stop raid in the opposite direction of the draw (i.e. a sweep of an hourly high since draw is lower).",
    "Step 3: Confirm the hourly high sweep occurs during the London session, accompanied by an SMT divergence with NQ.",
    "Step 4: Drop to the 5-minute ES chart and require a seller-above-open setup—wait for displacement lower and an inversion fair value gap closing through.",
    "Step 5: Enter short on the 5-minute inversion gap, targeting the daily fair value gap as the drawn liquidity objective."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade played out toward the target; analyst notes that using a failure swing for profit taking would have cost only half a point on ES while avoiding sitting through drawdown back to break even before the draw was hit.",
  "lessons": "Always anchor 5-minute entries to a higher time frame draw on liquidity (daily FVG/old low), confirm with an hourly sweep plus correlated SMT, and use failure swings for profit taking to avoid unnecessary drawdown.",
